### Intersection Types

Intersection types combine multiple types into one. The resulting type has all properties of each constituent type.

### Syntax

```typescript
type A = { a: number };
type B = { b: string };
type C = A & B;
// C has both a: number and b: string

const obj: C = { a: 1, b: "hello" };
```

### Multiple Intersections

```typescript
type HasName = { name: string };
type HasAge = { age: number };
type HasEmail = { email: string };

type User = HasName & HasAge & HasEmail;

const user: User = {
  name: "Alice",
  age: 30,
  email: "alice@example.com"
};
```

### Intersection with Interfaces

```typescript
interface Person {
  name: string;
  age: number;
}

interface Employee {
  employeeId: number;
  department: string;
}

type StaffMember = Person & Employee;

const staff: StaffMember = {
  name: "Bob",
  age: 25,
  employeeId: 456,
  department: "Engineering"
};
```

### Conflicting Property Types

```typescript
type A = { x: number };
type B = { x: string };
type C = A & B;
// C['x'] is never (number & string)
```

### Intersection vs Interface Extension

| Aspect | Intersection (&) | Interface extends |
|--------|-----------------|-------------------|
| Combining objects | Yes | Yes |
| Primitives | Yes (creates never) | No |
| Union types | Yes (distributes) | No |
| Declaration merging | No | Yes |

> **Key Point:** Intersection types merge all properties from all constituent types. Conflicting primitive types result in `never`.

codeExample:
type WithId = { id: number };
type WithTimestamp = { createdAt: Date; updatedAt: Date };
type WithMeta = { meta: Record<string, unknown> };

// Combined type
type DatabaseEntity = WithId & WithTimestamp & WithMeta;

const entity: DatabaseEntity = {
  id: 1,
  createdAt: new Date(),
  updatedAt: new Date(),
  meta: { version: 2 }
};

// Intersection with generics
type WithLogging<T> = T & { log: (message: string) => void };

function addLogging<T>(obj: T): WithLogging<T> {
  return {
    ...obj,
    log: (message: string) => console.log(message)
  };
}
